text: All browsers (but perhaps Chrome?) use a number (rather than a Date object).

author: 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6
text: Used to specify the time (in milliseconds relative to the epoch) at which the event was created. Due to the fact that some systems may not provide this information the value of timeStamp may be not available for all events. When not available, a value of 0 will be returned. Examples of epoch time are the time of the system start or 0:0:0 UTC 1st January 1970.

author: 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6
text: This read-only property is a Date object.

author: d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7
text: Probably relying on it as a sequence (for primitive ordering)

author: d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7
text: 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6: Has been metioned that it's complicated for implementors to return a Date.

author: d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7
text: bb21c722adad611b63dfb48ec99e8350: Can always convert timeStamp to date.

text: (A related question: if given two nested spans 'bolder' and 'lighter', should the inner span always be the same weight as outside the spans?)

text: if you have a font with three weights

text: then the innermost span would be the same weight as the outermost span, bolder than the text outside the spans

text: Hi, I'm looking for some vim configuration knob but can't seem to find anything even though I googled for fifteen minutes now. What I'm looking for is a vertical 'indicator' line in vim at column 80, but which does not enforce word wrapping.
